properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rain, heavy at times is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Significant rainfall expected. Total rainfall: 20 to 30 mm. Locations: Connaigre and Burin Peninsulas. Time span: overnight tonight to Monday afternoon. Remarks: The rainfall will be accompanied by temperatures a few degrees above zero. Areas with deep existing snow pack will be vulnerable to snowmelt and water runoff, with localized flooding possible. Where possible, the public is advised to clear storm drains prior to the rain in order to aid in water drainage. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow are expected. Up to 35 cm of snow is expected by tonight. A low pressure centre and associated surface trough pushing onshore along the northern Alaska Panhandle is spreading snow and strong winds to the South Klondike Highway and the Haines Road. Snowfall amounts will range from 25 to 35 cm for the Haines Road and 30 to 40 cm for the South Klondike Highway before the snow eases to night. Blowing snow will also be a concern due to strong south to southwest winds. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

Description: Temperatures in the minus thirties coupled with a moderate northwest wind will give extreme wind chills near minus 50 this morning. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia.
